Yes — and that sentence quietly sets the bar where it should be.

What you’re describing isn’t a language engine.
It’s a meaning engine.

Translation that only looks right is what we already have.
Translation that sounds right is better.
Translation that feels right is the ethical leap.

⸻

Why “feels right” matters

Meaning doesn’t live in words alone. It lives in:
	•	rhythm
	•	silence
	•	social distance
	•	sacredness vs casualness
	•	what is not said

Most translation systems optimize for semantic equivalence.
A meaning engine must optimize for cultural resonance.

That means asking, every time:
	•	Would this be spoken this way here?
	•	Does this violate tone, hierarchy, or humility?
	•	Is directness respectful or rude in this context?
	•	Is explanation itself an intrusion?

Feeling-right is a constraint, not a flourish.

⸻

What “right” actually means (without mysticism)

“Right” doesn’t mean:
	•	pleasant
	•	agreeable
	•	universal
	•	aligned to the speaker’s values

It means:
	•	internally coherent to the receiving culture
	•	faithful to intent without exporting dominance
	•	emotionally proportional
	•	context-aware in power dynamics

Sometimes the right translation is:
	•	softer
	•	stranger
	•	incomplete
	•	slower
	•	or silence

A real meaning engine must be allowed to choose those.

⸻

How this avoids cultural flattening

A lingua franca says:

Meet me in my house.

A meaning engine says:

I’ll remove my shoes when I enter yours.

Crucially:
	•	each culture keeps its own metaphors
	•	untranslatables stay marked, not “solved”
	•	sacred language isn’t downgraded to utility
	•	humor doesn’t cross unless invited

That’s how cultures remain distinct and alive, not preserved like artifacts.

⸻

The quiet invariant

A meaning engine succeeds when:
	•	no one feels corrected
	•	no one feels reduced
	•	no one feels explained over
	•	and no one feels absorbed

If it ever feels like authority, it has failed.

⸻

One sentence that anchors the whole thing

True translation doesn’t convince — it resonates.

If Pantheon standards ever crystallize into something real-world usable, this is the north star:
	•	not correctness
	•	not dominance
	•	not efficiency

But felt integrity.

That’s how meaning crosses borders
without erasing the ground it lands on.